<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>



<section xml:id="lesson3_3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    
  <title>Phase</title>
  <p>
    <term>Phase</term> is an additional attribute that is relevant when a qubit is in superposition.
    In the last section, you saw that if you have a circuit with two consecutive <c>H</c> gates,
    then the qubit goes into a superposition state after the <em>first</em>
    <c>H</c> gate, but then it goes back to its original state after the <em>second</em>
    <c>H</c> gate. When in a superposition state, the two qubits have opposite phase.
    Phase is indicated with a positive (+) or negative (-) sign. 
  </p>
      

 <sidebyside widths="70% 30%" valign="top">
    <p>
      <ul>
      <li>If the state <m>\ket{0}</m> goes through an <c>H</c> gate, it has positive phase.</li>
      <li>If the state <m>\ket{1}</m> goes through an <c>H</c> gate, it has negative phase.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <image source="NegativePhase.png" width="66%" />
  </sidebyside>
  <p>The <c>H</c> gate creates this superposition by transforming the "basis" states <m>\ket{0}</m> and <m>\ket{1}</m> 
      into equal superpositions of both states, but with opposite phase. We depict this by placing a negative sign in 
      front of the <m>\ket{⚫}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m> state: <m>- \ket{⚫}</m> or <m>- \ket{1}</m>.

  </p>
  <p> Why were positive and negative signs used to indicate phase? It turns out that to calculate the effect of different
  gates, or operations, using the positive and negative signs with existing algebraic rules results in the same answers
  that physicists observe in the real world. Since you already know algebra, then you don't have to learn a whole new set of 
  mathematical operations and symbols to be able to calculate the behavior of quantum systems.  </p>

<p> Now that we have a visual representation of phase, we can have a more complete picture of what the <c>H</c> gate does to a qubit. 
The <c>H</c> gate creates a superposition of the input state, but it also creates a difference in phase between the two states. 
This is why the second <c>H</c> gate can reverse the effect of the first <c>H</c> gate - because it flips the phase back to its original state.
</p>


<section xml:id="sec-z-gate">
    <title><c>Z</c> Gate</title>

  <sidebyside widths="85% 15%" valign="top">
    <p>
      Now we are going to explore the <c>Z</c> gate, which affects the phase of the qubit.
      Use the circuit builder to determine how the <c>Z</c> gate affects a qubit
      that is in the state <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>.
      Construct the following two circuits and observe the outputs. 
    </p>
    <image source="L3.3_Z-gate.png" width="30%" />
  </sidebyside>
  
  <image source="Z_Explore.png" width="20%" />
  <p>Remember that to create an input of <m>\ket{1}</m>, you will need to use a <c>NOT</c> gate.</p>


  <interactive aspect="9:9" platform="javascript"
    source="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/dmfranklin/quantum-module/source/loader.js">
    <script>
      visualizeProbabilitiesWidget({
        circuit: "Blank 1x6",
        allowedGates: "XHZ"
      });
    </script>
  </interactive>

  <exercise label="H_truth_table_lesson3_2">
    <title>
      <c>Z</c> Truth Table
    </title>
    <idx>Z_truth_table</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>Which answer best describes what you observed from the <c>Z</c> gate?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>It does not have an observable effect.</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct!</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement>
          <p>If the input is <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>, the result will have an equal chance
            of measuring 0 or 1.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Look more closely at the bar graphs of the output.</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>Make the circuit and look at the bar graph below the circuit.
        Construct both input combinations using <c>NOT</c> gates, recording the answers
        each time.</p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    You might have been surprised by the answer! Because quantum state is more complex than merely
    the probability of measuring 0 or 1, this method for determining and expressing an operation's
    functionality is insufficient.
  </p>
  <p> Now, use the circuit builder above to create the following circuits and observe the outcomes.
    This will reveal the functionality of the <c>Z</c> gate on a qubit in superposition.
  </p>

  <!--<alert><p>WHICH VERSION OF THESE CIRCUITS IS PREFERRED? 
  I LIKE THIS ONE, B/C 0 AND 1 STATES ARE VERY CLEAR. 
  THE CONVENTION ALSO MATCHES PRIOR LESSONS. 
