  <image source="Z_Explore_2.png" width="50%" />
  
  <!--
  <p><em>(Remember that to create an input of <m>\ket{1}</m>, you will need to use a <c>NOT</c> gate, as shown here:)</em></p>
  <image source="Checkpoint3.2-Z-gate-behavior-with-Superposition.png" width="75%" />
  -->

  <exercise label="Superposition Z">
    <title>
      <c>Z</c> Gate Behavior with Superposition
    </title>
    <idx>superpositionZ</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>What is the effect of the sequence <c>H</c>-<c>Z</c>-<c>H</c> on qubits beginning in <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>
          \ket{1}
        </m>?</p>
      <image source="Checkpoint3.2-Z-gate-behavior-with-Superposition.png" width="66%" />
      <!--<image source="Z_Explore_2.png" width="50%" />-->
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="no">
        <statement>
          <p>There is an equal chance of measuring 0 or 1.</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p> </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
          <p>No observable effect. </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p> </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
          <p>The same as a <c>NOT</c> gate</p>
        </statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>Correct!</p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>Think about what the output would be after each gate.</p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>
  <p>
    Now we see that <c>Z</c> does have a major effect on the system, but <em>only</em> when the
    qubit is in superposition.  The truth table for the <c>Z</c> gate is below. I suggest adding this to your page of notes.
     </p><p>
     <image source="L3.2-Z-gate-truth-table.png" width="30%" />
  </p>
 <p> This truth table does not seem right - you already observed that there is no observable effect
 when a Z gate is applied to a qubit in the <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m> state. So why is the truth table
 expressed this way? We have to remember that the truth table is describing the effect of the Z gate on the full quantum state,
 including phase, not just the measurement outcomes. When a Z gate is applied to a qubit in the <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m> state,
 there is no change in phase, so the effect is not observable. However, when a Z gate is applied to a qubit in superposition, 
 it flips the phase of the states, and the negative sign is always applied to the probability of the <m>\ket{1}</m> state.
 </p><p>
 <image source="Z_Gate_Effect_1.png" width="75%" />
 </p>

